ook shows the degree to which this work departs radically from the legacy of the French New Wave, and in many ways shows signs of having been formed by the distinct culture of Switzerland, to which Godard and Miéville returned in the 1970s to set up their “atelier,” Sonimage. Two Bicycles offers a chance to explore a body of work that is as unique and demanding as it is rich and revelatory. Godard and Miéville have worked together for four decades but have never seemed more relevant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszFrance. 0aMotion picture producers and directorszSwitzerland. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCinema.  aGodard.  aSwiss.  aTelevision.  aVideo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458936440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554589364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554589364/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles